### CATEGORY F — PERFORMANCE AND STABILITY
*These will cause the game to become unplayable under normal conditions.*

**F1 — Condition evaluation at 240 evaluations/second**
TASK-075 evaluates unlock conditions for all LOCKED nodes and upgrade conditions for all ACTIVE nodes every tick. At full 24 nodes × 10 ticks/second = 240 evaluations/second. Some conditions (energy_accumulated scanning all nodes) are O(N) each. No task throttles this evaluation.

**F2 — No NaN/infinity guards**
With 240+ T1 nodes each performing float arithmetic simultaneously, a single division-by-zero (e.g., getT2Pressure when capacity=0 before T1 nodes have any quality) will produce NaN. NaN propagates multiplicatively — one NaN in one node's pressure will corrupt meridian flow, then adjacent nodes, then attributes. No task adds defensive guards.

**F3 — Fast-forward requires multi-tick per interval, not shorter interval**
TASK-245 mentions 10× speed. If implemented as setInterval at 10× the rate, ticks would need to fire at 100Hz. Browser setInterval cannot reliably fire at this rate. The correct approach is to execute N ticks per interval call. No task addresses this implementation detail, and TASK-006's SimulationClock has no multi-tick support.

**F4 — Meridian ID collision for reverse meridians**
TASK-047 creates meridian with id like `'muladhara→svadhisthana'`. TASK-057 creates the reverse with id `'svadhisthana→muladhara'`. This convention works IF all meridian IDs are unique. But no task creates a centralized ID generation function. Different tasks creating meridians may use different separator characters or ordering conventions, causing silent ID collisions.

---

### CATEGORY G — MISSING FEEDBACK SYSTEMS
*The player cannot understand what is happening.*

**G1 — No notification/event display system**
Many tasks fire events (UnlockEvent, LevelUpEvent, BreakthroughEvent, NodeDamageEvent, StateChangeEvent). No task creates a UI notification queue to display them to the player. Events are emitted into a void.

**G2 — No routing feedback when energy cannot flow**
If a player sets all weights routing toward IO_OUT but the IO_OUT node is full (at capacity from unemptied energy), energy backs up with no visual indication. Similarly if IO_IN fills up and the meridian can no longer inject. No task defines a "routing blocked" indicator.

**G3 — No undo for weight changes**
A player who accidentally drags an edge weight to 0 (cutting off a critical path) or sets all outgoing weights incorrectly has no recovery mechanism. No task implements undo for weight changes. Given that weight management is the primary moment-to-moment interaction, this is a significant usability gap.

